body:
Hey I just push a first update:
- fresh rebase
- useÂ block_max_time instead of blocktime followingÂ ryanofsky advice
- faster functionalÂ test with jonatack recommandation.

TheÂ block_max_time advantage is clear for me now, because blocktime couldÂ sometimesÂ  not be orderedÂ in strict chronological order. block_max_time prevents this and Foundblock helper is very practical to get it.

Following jonatack recommandation, the test is now faster and validates the exact same thing as my previous iteration.

But this update doesn't contain any change concerning theÂ wtxOrdered list.
I can't wrap my head around the fact that ryanofskyÂ and jonatack sees a way to change this to obtain a better code.

At first glance, I thought I would do this first: 

> Another code cleanup that would be nice to see is movingÂ nTimeReceived,Â nOrderPos, andÂ wtxOrderedÂ updates inside theÂ ComputeTimeSmartÂ function instead of doing them before

To cleanup the code first and change the behavior withÂ rescanning_old_block after.
But I don't think it's a good ideaÂ to do that : currently, ComputeTimeSmart has no side effect on the wtx transaction. It's a good thing for me. If I do that, and you look at the resultingÂ AddToWallet function : the fInsertedNew path will populate wtx via side effects in the ComputeTimeSmart function and the !fInsertedNew path willÂ populate it directly in AddToWallet function. I don't like this type of asymetricÂ + side effects behaviors inÂ variousÂ execution path, but I'm open to understand the way things are done in Bitcoin Core and in C++ (I don't have any experience in C++).

After that, I just tried the simplest approach:
```
if (fInsertedNew) {
Â  Â  Â  Â  wtx.m_confirm = confirm;
Â  Â  Â  Â  wtx.nTimeReceived = chain().getAdjustedTime();
Â  Â  Â  Â  if(!rescanning_old_block) {
Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  wtx.nOrderPos = IncOrderPosNext(&batch);
Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  Â  wtx.m_it_wtxOrdered = wtxOrdered.insert(std::make_pair(wtx.nOrderPos, &wtx));
Â  Â  Â  Â  }
Â  Â  Â  Â  wtx.nTimeSmart = ComputeTimeSmart(wtx, rescanning_old_block);
Â  Â  Â  Â  AddToSpends(hash);
Â  Â  }
```

But this makeÂ me scratched my head : In theÂ rescanning_old_block case, wtx object will be left with uninitialized field. I'm pretty sure it could produce error somewhere else... maybe not ifÂ nOrderPos != -1 is always checked before manipulatingÂ m_it_wtxOrdered, but a minima it requires more prudence to manipulate this. To be clear : I'm inconfortable because I don't visualise all consequences.

And after that , I looked at the wtxOrderedÂ usage, and that's where my head explode : This list has two usages at the same time:
- the first is to maintain an ordered list for ComputeTimeSmart. The ordered aspect is only used here. That's why I understand why ryanofsky want to remove the transaction from here in the first place.
- the second usage is from RPC interface in the listtransactions method. And here I don't think that transaction order has impact (not sure, but highly probable), but I'm sure that absence of a wallet transaction has impact. I can't remove theÂ wtxOrdered insertion inÂ rescanning_old_block scenario without breaking things here.

That's why I'm stuck and don't understand the way you two see it in the first place. Could you please help me here ? I'll be happy to better understand implicationsÂ here and way to move around this problem here !

The only way I could thing about refactoring it, is to separate the two list : maintain one unordered with all transactions and one ordered withÂ transaction for ComputeTimeSmart only... but I doesn't make any sense for me to do that and I can't envision a step after this move to obtain a clearer code after that.

